29. **[Siletz Agency Site](/Siletz_Agency_Site)**
    *   **Image:** Siletz Agency Site
    *   **Date listed:** January 1, 1976 (&#35;76001582)
    *   **Location:** Siletz–Logsden Rd., 44°43′23″N 123°54′38″W, [Siletz](/Siletz,_Oregon)
    *   **Description:** The [Siletz Agency Site](/Siletz_Agency_Site) is not merely a collection of historical buildings; it is a profoundly significant, and often painful, landmark in the history of [Native Americans in the United States](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) and the [Oregon](/Oregon) coast. Beginning in 1855, the [U.S. Army](/United_States_Army) undertook the forced relocation of over 2,600 individuals from [several different tribes](/Confederated_Tribes_of_Siletz_Indians) to the newly established [Siletz Reservation](/Siletz_Reservation). The federal government then established an [Indian agency](/Indian_agency) at Siletz in 1857, ostensibly to manage and "civilize" the relocated tribes. However, the reality was one of immense hardship, disease, and cultural suppression, which tragically reduced the indigenous population to approximately 600 within just three decades. By the time the agency finally closed its doors in 1925, the area known as "Government Hill" had expanded to include a [blockhouse](/Blockhouse), a [boarding house](/Boarding_house), a [schoolhouse](/School) (intended to assimilate children), a [barn](/Barn), an [office building](/Office_building), various employee [residences](/House), a [hospital](/Hospital)/[meeting house](/Meeting_house), and a [cemetery](/Cemetery) – many of which have since been lost to time. Despite the destruction, the site remains an absolutely vital focal point for members of the [Siletz tribes](/Confederated_Tribes_of_Siletz_Indians), a place of memory, resilience, and ongoing cultural connection. It stands as a stark reminder of the devastating impact of federal Indian policy and the enduring spirit of indigenous communities.

